в•ӯв”Җ Assistant [MainThread@842059] в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                             в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The transformation `shuffle(select(cond, A, B))` into `select(cond, shuffle(A, B),         в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ shuffle(A, B))` is generally a valid optimization. However, it becomes incorrect in the    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ presence of `poison` values, as `poison` propagation rules can be violated.                в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ In this specific case, the original IR is:                                                 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ```llvm                                                                                    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ %sel = select i1 %cmp, <4 x i8> %y, <4 x i8> <i8 0, i8 poison, i8 0, i8 poison>            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ %shuf = shufflevector <4 x i8> %sel, <4 x i8> <i8 poison, i8 1, i8 poison, i8 3>, <4 x     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ i32> <i32 0, i32 5, i32 2, i32 7>                                                          в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ```                                                                                        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The transformed IR is:                                                                     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ```llvm                                                                                    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ %1 = shufflevector <4 x i8> %y, <4 x i8> <i8 poison, i8 1, i8 poison, i8 3>, <4 x i32>     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ <i32 0, i32 5, i32 2, i32 7>                                                               в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ %shuf = select i1 %cmp, <4 x i8> %1, <4 x i8> <i8 0, i8 1, i8 0, i8 3>                     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ```                                                                                        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The problem arises when the select condition `%cmp` is `poison`.                           в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ *   **In the source IR:**                                                                  в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ     1.  `%sel` becomes `<poison, poison, poison, poison>` because the condition is         в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ `poison`.                                                                                  в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ     2.  `%shuf` becomes `shufflevector(<poison, poison, poison, poison>, <poison, 1,       в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ poison, 3>, <0, 5, 2, 7>)`.                                                                в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ     3.  The result is `<poison, 1, poison, 3>`. The `1` and `3` are selected from the      в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ second vector operand, which are not `poison`.                                             в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ *   **In the transformed IR:**                                                             в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ     1.  The `select` instruction is now the final operation.                               в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ     2.  The true value is the result of shuffling `%y`. If `%y` is all `poison`, this is   в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ `<poison, 1, poison, 3>`.                                                                  в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ     3.  The false value is `<i8 0, i8 1, i8 0, i8 3>`.                                     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ     4.  Since the condition `%cmp` is `poison` and the true/false values of the `select`   в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ are different, the entire result becomes `<poison, poison, poison, poison>`.               в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ Comparing the results, the source produces `<poison, 1, poison, 3>` while the target       в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ produces `<poison, poison, poison, poison>`. The transformation has incorrectly introduced в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ more `poison` values, which is a miscompilation.                                           в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                                               в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The `opt` log confirms that the transformation is happening inside `instcombine` and       в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ specifically points to `FoldOpIntoSelect`.                                                 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ```                                                                                        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ IC: Old =   %shuf = shufflevector <4 x i8> %sel, <4 x i8> <i8 poison, i8 1, i8 poison, i8  в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 3>, <4 x i32> <i32 0, i32 5, i32 2, i32 7>                                                 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ     New =   <badref> = select i1 %cmp, <4 x i8> %1, <4 x i8> <i8 0, i8 1, i8 0, i8 3>      в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ```                                                                                        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ This shows `instcombine` is pushing the `shufflevector` operation (`Op`) into the `select` в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ instruction (`SI`). The log shows the creation of a new `select` instruction where the     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ `shufflevector` has been applied to both arms.                                             в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                                 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The root cause is in the `InstCombinerImpl::FoldOpIntoSelect` function. This function      в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ attempts to simplify `Op(select(C, T, F))` into `select(C, Op(T), Op(F))`.                 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The logic proceeds as follows:                                                             в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 1.  It checks if either arm of the `select` is a constant. In our case, the false arm is   в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ the constant vector `<i8 0, i8 poison, i8 0, i8 poison>`.                                  в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 2.  It then calls `constantFoldOperationIntoSelectOperand` to see if applying the          в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ operation (`shufflevector`) to the constant arm results in a new constant.                 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 3.  `constantFoldOperationIntoSelectOperand` successfully folds `shufflevector(<0, poison, в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 0, poison>, ...)` into the constant `<0, 1, 0, 3>`.                                        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 4.  Crucially, the resulting constant `<0, 1, 0, 3>` does *not* contain `poison`. The      в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ `FoldOpIntoSelect` logic sees this and proceeds with the transformation, unaware that the  в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ original constant operand *did* contain `poison`.                                          в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The fundamental flaw is the assumption that if `Op(Constant)` is `poison`-free, the        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ transformation is safe. This is incorrect because the presence of `poison` in the original в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ constant can affect the result when the `select` condition itself is `poison`. The         в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ transformation changes the order of operations, altering how `poison` from the condition   в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ interacts with `poison` from the data, leading to the miscompilation.                      в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ To fix this, `FoldOpIntoSelect` must be more conservative. If any of the `select`'s        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ constant arms contain `poison`, this transformation should be disabled, as it is not       в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ generally safe.                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The fix is to add a check at the beginning of `FoldOpIntoSelect` to bail out if either of  в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ the `select`'s operands is a constant that contains `poison`.                              в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp`                       в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ```cpp                                                                                     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ // Edit at line 1718                                                                       в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp                             в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp                             в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ @@ -1715,6 +1715,13 @@                                                                     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ        if ((TV == Op0 && FV == Op1) || (FV == Op0 && TV == Op1))                           в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ          return nullptr;                                                                   в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ      }                                                                                     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ    }                                                                                       в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ +  // If one of the arms of the select is a constant that contains poison,                 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ +  // folding the operation into the select is unsafe because it can change how            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ +  // poison propagates.                                                                   в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ +  if ((isa<Constant>(TV) && cast<Constant>(TV)->containsPoison()) ||                      в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ +      (isa<Constant>(FV) && cast<Constant>(FV)->containsPoison()))                        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ +    return nullptr;                                                                       в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ +                                                                                          в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ    // Make sure that one of the select arms constant folds successfully.                   в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ    Value *NewTV = constantFoldOperationIntoSelectOperand(Op, SI, /*IsTrueArm*/ true);      в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ    Value *NewFV = constantFoldOperationIntoSelectOperand(Op, SI, /*IsTrueArm*/ false);     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ```                                                                                        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                          в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ                                                                                            в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ The proposed edit adds a guard to `FoldOpIntoSelect` that prevents it from folding an      в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ operation into a `select` if one of the `select`'s arms is a constant containing `poison`. в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ This change correctly identifies the unsafe condition demonstrated by the reproducer and   в”Ӯ
